That posture was matched by action. In Virginia, career prosecutor Elizabeth Yusi told colleagues she saw no probable cause to charge New York Attorney General Letitia James with mortgage fraud, despite pressure from Trump allies. She planned to decline the case. In response, the administration replaced her boss, installing Lindsey Halligan, a former Trump personal attorney, as U.S. attorney. Halligan promptly took the same thin case to a grand jury and secured an indictment of James, even as senior prosecutors resigned or refused to participate. In parallel, Halligan delivered an indictment of former FBI Director James Comey on charges of lying to Congress, after Trump had publicly demanded that his enemies be prosecuted. Both James and Comey pleaded not guilty and vowed to challenge the cases as vindictive. The pattern was plain. When neutral prosecutors balked, loyal ones were brought in to do what the president wanted.\
