Chicago became the test case for how far those claims would be pushed. Trump authorized the deployment of 300 Illinois National Guard troops and 200 more from Texas to \'93protect\'94 ICE facilities and federal property around the city. Illinois Governor JB Pritzker called the move an invasion and filed suit, joined by Chicago\'92s mayor. They argued that there was no rebellion or insurrection in Illinois, and that the deployment violated state sovereignty and the Posse Comitatus tradition. U.S. District Judge April Perry initially declined to block the deployment while she studied the case, allowing Texas troops to arrive at an Army reserve center outside Chicago. Within days, as more evidence came in and public pressure mounted, she issued a two\uc0\u8209 week order halting the Guard deployment, finding no credible evidence of rebellion. The pause was temporary, but it showed that courts could still force the executive to slow down.\
